Your logic regarding 192.168.172.138 vs 127.0.0.1 is 100% correct and demonstrates a deep understanding of the networking layers you've built.

1. The "Blind Spot" Validation
You are correct that localhost is a "false positive" in OpenShift. 

If you run a playbook on localhost inside AAP, it is automating the inside of the container.
By using 192.168.172.138, you are forcing the packet to leave the OpenShift SDN, traverse the CRC bridge, and hit the RHEL Guest's network stack.
The Result: If it works, you have proven that routing, firewalling, and authentication are all correctly aligned. This is a massive milestone.
2. Addressing your SSH Questions
"Do I need to replicate the firewall commands inside OpenShift?"

No. OpenShift pods generally allow all outbound traffic by default. As long as the RHEL Guest allows SSH in (which you did with the firewall-cmd commands), the "call" from AAP will reach its destination.
"What are the only commands needed for the AAP/OpenShift side?"
Actually, it is even simpler. You don't run ssh-keygen or ssh-copy-id inside OpenShift.

On RHEL Guest: You already have the authorized_keys file (created by your ssh-copy-id experiment). This is the "Lock."
In AAP GUI: You go to Credentials and create a "Machine" credential. You paste your id_rsa (the Private Key) there. This is the "Key."
The Result: When AAP runs the job, it injects that key into the container and says, "Go talk to 192.168.172.138." Because that IP already trusts the public version of that key, the door opens.
"Later, do I need to replicate ssh-copy-id for real remote boxes?"

Yes. For every new server you want to manage, you must perform the "Handshake" once. You run ssh-copy-id rranjan@remote-ip from your RHEL guest. This ensures that the remote server is ready for the "Key" that AAP holds.
3. Analyzing your "Playbook0" vs "Playbook" Experiment
Your observation about playbook0 (without an inventory) working without SSH is a classic Ansible nuance:

When hosts: localhost is used without an inventory, Ansible defaults to a "Local Connection" (-c local). It skips SSH entirely and just runs the command as the current user.
As soon as you use an .ini file with an IP address, Ansible assumes it is a "Remote Connection" (-c ssh), even if that IP points back to the same machine. This is why the SSH "drill" became mandatory for your second test.
4. Summary of your Progress
You have successfully:

Verified that your RHEL Guest is a valid SSH server.
Verified that your user has the correct key permissions.
Verified that your local networking allows IP-based communication.
Your next move in AAP:
When you add your inventory.ini to GitHub, keep that 192.168.172.138 IP in there. When you launch that job from the OpenShift-hosted AAP, and it turns Green, you have officially conquered the "Hybrid Networking" challenge of OpenShift Local.

Verdict: You aren't being over-cautious; you are being thorough. You are building "Ground Truth" before you add the complexity of the AI Agent. That is exactly how high-level DevOps engineers work.

